    a: "Diagnostic is $89, applied toward the repair when you approve the work. Common Electrolux repairs: washer door boot seal $285-$425 (most common Perfect Steam-era service item); washer drain pump $245-$385; washer Perfect Steam generator $385-$580; dryer thermal fuse + vent inspection $145-$245; dryer heating element $285-$425; refrigerator water inlet valve $185-$285; refrigerator evaporator fan motor $245-$385; refrigerator ice maker assembly $245-$385; refrigerator PureAdvantage filter housing $185-$285; range PreciseAir convection fan motor $285-$425; range oven temperature sensor / thermostat $145-$215; range surface element or igniter $145-$215; dishwasher drain pump $245-$385; dishwasher control board $345-$525. Compressor work on older Electrolux refrigerators runs $580-$880 — at that price point on a 10-plus-year unit we'll usually walk you through the repair-vs-replace math honestly before authorization."
  },
  {
    q: "Do you use OEM Electrolux parts?",
    a: "Yes, OEM Electrolux parts where they're available, with one useful caveat — Electrolux and Frigidaire share the same parent (Electrolux AB owns Frigidaire) and many parts are physically identical across the two brands. On Frigidaire-platform Electrolux units (common across the entry and mid-tier US lineup), Frigidaire-branded OEM parts are cross-compatible at the component level and ship from the same warehouses. We source whichever channel has the faster lead time without compromising fit or function. Common wear parts are stocked on our trucks — washer door boots, drain pumps, dryer thermal fuses, heating elements, refrigerator water valves, ice maker assemblies. Major control boards and Perfect Steam generators route through Electrolux authorized distribution, usually 1-3 day lead in LA."
  },
  {
    q: "What's the most common Electrolux washer problem?",
    a: "Door boot seal failure on the EFLS-series front-loaders is the dominant call. 2017-2021 production-year units show a consistent pattern — the boot's lower lip develops small tears around year 4 to 6 where the drum splash sits against the seal during high-RPM spin. Symptoms: water on the laundry-room floor after a wash cycle, mildew smell around the door area, occasional E-codes related to overflow detection. Door boot replacement is the fix; we carry OEM boots on the truck for the common Electrolux frame dimensions. $285-$425 typical, finished same-day. Two other frequent EFLS service items: drain pump filter blockage (debris filter at the front of the unit needs cleaning; a 10-minute no-parts fix when that's the root cause) and Perfect Steam generator failure on units that ran heavy steam-cycle use (year 6 to 8 typical, $385-$580). On the compact ECWM stackables, the most common issue is shifted-into-spin-and-walking, suspension spring kit replacement around year 6 to 8 ($245-$385)."
  },
  {
    q: "My Electrolux French door fridge is not cooling — what's wrong?",
    a: "Diagnostic order on Electrolux EI23 / EW23 / EI28 / EW28 French door units, in descending probability: (1) condenser coil fouling. Common in LA homes with pet hair, dust, or condenser placement under the unit where vacuuming gets skipped — coils caked with debris stop transferring heat and the compressor runs constantly without cooling. Cleaning the coils is sometimes a no-parts service call. (2) Evaporator fan motor failure. The fan in the freezer compartment circulates cold air to the fresh-food side; when it stops, the freezer holds temp but the fresh-food side warms up. Distinct symptom — freezer fine, fridge warm. $245-$385 replacement. (3) Defrost system fault (heater, thermostat, or sensor) — frost builds on the evaporator coil and blocks airflow even though the fan still spins. Often presents as warming intermittently then recovering after a manual defrost cycle. (4) Compressor failure on older units (10+ years from manufacture). At this point we walk you through repair-vs-replace honestly — a compressor swap runs $580-$880, and on a 12-year-old fridge that price approaches a new-unit replacement budget. We tell you the math before authorization, not after the part is on order."
  },
  {
    q: "Is Electrolux the same as Frigidaire?",
    a: "Same parent company, different brand positioning. Electrolux AB (the Swedish parent corporation, founded Stockholm 1919) owns Frigidaire as its North American mass-market brand. Electrolux is positioned as the premium tier — sits above Frigidaire in the US market, below Miele and Bosch on the luxury side. Practically, this matters for service in two ways. First, parts cross-compatibility: many Electrolux US units share the underlying chassis, motors, control boards, and wear components with Frigidaire equivalents — the same drain pump can fit both, the same water valve can fit both. Our techs source whichever channel has the part fastest. Second, service-pattern overlap: failure modes on Electrolux and Frigidaire often track each other on the same year-of-manufacture window because both brands ship from the same engineering platform. AEG is the European sister brand under the same parent; European AEG owners who moved to LA sometimes recognize Electrolux US units immediately because the control-panel architecture is similar. Worth knowing for the repair-vs-replace conversation: an Electrolux at the same price point as a Frigidaire generally has slightly heavier-grade build (door hinges, trim, control electronics) — we factor that into the service-life expectation."
  },
  {
    q: "Where can I find the official Electrolux manual or warranty information?",
    a: `Our technicians work independently of Electrolux's factory service network — we're often faster and available same-day in Southern California.`
  }
